description: background pre-processing filter and sliding based training algorithm for object detection on COCO datasets

We train neural networks with depth of over 150 layers for classification, detection, and segmentation. We propose a “deep residual learning” framework [a] that eases the optimization and convergence of extremely deep networks. Our “deep residual nets” enjoy accuracy gains when the networks are substantially deeper than those used previously. Such accuracy gains are not witnessed for many common networks when going deeper. Our instance semantic system is based on our work in [b]. We build a Multi-task Network Cascade for proposing regions, regressing masks, and categorizing instances. We develop an end-to-end algorithm for training this causal, cascaded system. In particular, we propose an “RoI warping” layer that is differentiable with respect to the region coordinates, so the entire backpropagation can be performed in a theoretically valid way. Our object detection system is based on the “Faster R-CNN” system in our NIPS paper [c]. The region proposal network (RPN) in Faster R-CNN effectively learns the proposals on the COCO dataset, and the result in this submission is obtained by using only 300 proposals per image for a single model. The object detection network is built based on the observations in [d]. Both object detection and instance segmentation systems benefit greatly from the extremely deep residual networks. On the COCO detection dataset, Faster R-CNN with a 101-layer residual net shows 30% relative improvement over the counterpart Faster R-CNN with VGG-16. The training set for the classification network is the 1000-class ImageNet training set. The training set for the detection task is the MS COCO trainval set with box-level annotations. The training set for the segmentation task is the MS COCO trainval set with mask-level annotations. [a] “Deep Residual Learning for Image Recognition”, Kaiming He, Xiangyu Zhang, Shaoqing Ren, Jian Sun. Tech Report 2015. [b] “Instance-aware semantic segmentation via multi-task network cascades”, Jifeng Dai, Kaiming He, Jian Sun. Tech Report 2015. [c] “Faster R-CNN: Towards Real-Time Object Detection with Region Proposal Networks”, Shaoqing Ren, Kaiming He, Ross Girshick, Jian Sun. NIPS 2015. [d] “Object Detection Networks on Convolutional Feature Maps”, Shaoqing Ren, Kaiming He, Ross Girshick, Xiangyu Zhang, Jian Sun. arXiv 2015.

description: We empirically investigate two complementary methods of improving object detection: (1) we incorporate global image context using stacked lateral recurrent neural networks with rectified linear units and (2) we use skip connections to pool from many different layers in the network and combine them with L2 normalization and re-scaling.  We use a single VGG16 ConvNet model based on Fast R-CNN, with a mix of proposal boxes from MCG (Multiscale Combinatorial Grouping) and RPN (Region Proposal Network, from Faster R-CNN).  We have no augmentation or ensembling at test time (single ConvNet, single scale, single crop, and no flipping).  The method will be posted to arXiv soon, and open source code will be released.  Runtime: ~2.7s per image on a Titan X GPU to evaluate 4000 candidate boxes (excluding proposal generation).

description: We use CNN to segment and detect objects. We use a patch merging step to generate final results.
This method is developed based on fast rcnn.

Our approach is built on DeepMask proposals fed into the Fast R-CNN pipeline. The DeepMask proposals have been substantially improved to encourage proposal diversity and mask quality. We also augmented our CNN classifier with a novel foveal structure, skip-connections, an improved cost function that encourages better localization, and a few additional modifications. Finally we utilize aggressive ensembling (model and inference) to further improve performance.

description: We use AZ-Net to generate region proposal. The detector is Fast R-CNN. Both models are trained on MS COCO trainval set, using VGG 16 models pre-trained on ImageNet. The region proposals are augmented with six neighboring boxes. The test time is 380 ms per image.  The Fast R-CNN detector is trained at 400k iterations.
We use hard example mining to train Fast R-CNN (submitted to CVPR16).
